04517nam a22006735i 9781487596224DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191982onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875962247 a10.3138/97814875962242doi  a(DE-B1597)513923  a(OCoLC)1088907111  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPT2621.R27bZ56165 1982eb 7aPER0110002bisacsh04a838.912091 aGRIMSTAD, Karl, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMasks of the Prophet :bThe Theatrical World of Karl Kraus /cKarl GRIMSTAD. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1982  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. The Gadfly: 1892 to June 1901 -- t2. The Knight-in-shining-armour. October 1901 to 1909 -- t3 The Prophet: 1910-8 -- t4 The Grand Inquisitor: 1919 to April 1930 -- t5 The Defeated Idealist: May 1930 to June 1936 -- tConclusion -- tAPPENDIX: A Chronology of Die Packel -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a'When the name "Hitler" is mentioned, nothing occurs to me' – so said Karl Kraus. For this leading Viennese Jewish critic and intellectual the touchstone of art was ethics. How could he be speechless in the face of a threat to all that ethics means? To answer this question, the author makes a detailed chronological study of Kraus's intellectual activity as reflected in his work on the theatre. The results are presented in five chapters, each dealing with a different 'mask' adopted by Kraus during the period 1892-1936. Grimstad considers not only theatre and drama criticism in Die Fackel and Kraus's dramatic writings, but also biographical data, to help uncover the rationale of his work. That rationale is the logic of the theatrical mode in which he lived and wrote. The stage was not only his subject matter, it determined what he would see and say. Grimstad argues that when Kraus wrote, his words were the speech of an 'actor' who was often infatuated with himself and obsessed with the need to overwhelm his rival 'actors.' When Hitler's storm-troopers began their march, he could say nothing for the world in which his thought took shape had become a world of theatrics, not 'Realpolitik.' Kraus criticized plays without reading them and performances without seeing them, obsessed with the belief that his was the voice of all that was true, good, and beautiful. Grimstad observes that he was a prophet who confused the divine inspiration with the Thespian urge, playing to an audience, using a mask for each of his roles, yet thinking he spoke to all mankind, bringing them pure ethos. This volume will be of particular interest to those working in the fields of theatre criticism, comparative literature, German literature, and Jewish intellectual history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Theater / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148759622440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487596224423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487596224.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK